        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down</placeName>
                    <date>May 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Willy</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>We have got your Sunday &amp; Tuesday letters.— Will you tell M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Kynnersley<ref target="#foot.f2"/> that I am very sorry to say that really have not <hi rend="underline">one</hi> single aquaintance left in S. America: it is now 24–25 years since I was there, &amp; the English population is a floating &amp; changeable one.—</p>
<p>Mamma has used you very ill, &amp; quite forgot about your Flute, but I have found it, &amp; it shall go off tomorrow morning by the Post together with this note.— So you may “tootle” to your heart’s content. What a dining out gentleman you have become!—</p>
<p>With respect to allowance we will settle it this summer Holidays: <hi rend="superscript">£</hi>40 sounds a good lot, nearly as much as Parslow’s wages;<ref target="#foot.f3"/> but I daresay it is not too much. Try &amp; find out more particulars, &amp; whether any other Boys have an allowance.—</p>
<p>Mamma, Miss Thorley &amp; Etty returned yesterday:<ref target="#foot.f4"/> I grieve to say Etty is not one bit better: everything must bend to her health, &amp; Mamma will take her to Moor Park in a fortnight’s time, stay a fortnight, &amp; then I shall go there again for a bit.—<ref target="#foot.f5"/> What we shall do in summer, it is really impossible to say: if we do not go to Malvern, we will try our best to think of some lark or amusement for all of you.—<ref target="#foot.f6"/> Mamma thinks if Water Cure does suit Etty, we had better go to Malvern to complete it, but I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. prefer leaving her longer at Moor Park.—<ref target="#foot.f7"/> It is very disheartening for me, that all the wonderful good which Moor Park did me at the time, has gone all away like a flash of lightening, now that I am at work again. And eheu, eheu, I have left off Snuff for nothing!—<ref target="#foot.f8"/></p>
<p>On Friday Aunt Susan is coming, on Saturday Uncle Harry &amp; Aunt Jessie, on Monday Fanny Frank, &amp; on tomorrow week Aunt Catherine, so we have lots of visitors expected,—a good lot too many, now poor dear Etty is so indifferent.<ref target="#foot.f9"/></p>
<p>What a <hi rend="underline">capital</hi> Hand you have directed your two last notes in; it was quite Ducal.—</p>
<p>Ever my dear Son | Your’ affect Father | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.2 am very sorry to say that] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">5.1 Aunt] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n3">5.2 tomorrow] ‘t’ <hi rend="italic">over illeg</hi></note>
